  "prompt": "What is 6/6 myopia vision?",
  "response": "In the context of vision testing, 6/6 vision (or 20/20 vision in the imperial system) is considered \"normal\" or \"perfect\" vision. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. 6/6 vision means:\n- A person can clearly see at 6 meters what a person with standard vision can see at 6 meters\n- This represents good visual acuity and sharpness\n- No corrective lenses are needed to see clearly\n\n2. Myopia (near-sightedness) is different from 6/6 vision:\n- Myopia means a person can see near objects clearly, but distant objects are blurry\n- Myopia is measured in degrees (-0.25, -0.50, -1.00, etc.)\n- Someone with myopia would typically have vision worse than 6/6, such as 6/12 or 6/18\n\n3. If someone has both 6/6 vision and myopia, it means:\n- Their distant vision can be corrected to 6/6 with glasses or contact lenses\n- Without correction, distant objects appear blurry\n\nSo, 6/6 and myopia are not the same thing - they describe different aspects of vision.",
